{
  "doc_id": "4000",
  "text": "ADRENOCORTICAL carcinoma (ACC) is a rare malignancy associated with poor prognosis [CITATION_1] 2] . Clinical and pathological feature as well as its approach to therapy is hampered by its low incidence (1-2/1,000,000/year) and heterogeneity [CITATION_2] 2] . Tumors may be functional or nonfunctional depending on whether they produce biological active steroids, such as cortisol, aldosterone, androgens or estrogens. Disorganized expression of steroidogenic enzymes in individual carcinoma cells is considered to lead to ineffective corticosteroidogenesis, characteristic of altered steroid metabolism in ACC [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . We report herein a very rare case of estrogen-secreting ACC associated with subclinical Cushing's syndrome in whom detailed analysis by endocrinological, biochemical, immunohistochemical, and pathological studies was conducted.",
